('spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement:learn:2ac9efb8', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement', 'G.2 Adjectives and Agreement', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "How do adjectives agree with the noun?", "reading": "<p>In Spanish, adjectives must <strong>agree</strong> with the noun they describe — in both <strong>gender</strong> (masculine/feminine) and <strong>number</strong> (singular/plural). Most adjectives end in <strong>-o</strong> for masculine and change to <strong>-a</strong> for feminine; add <strong>-s</strong> for the plural.</p>\n            <table class=\"vocab-tbl\">\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"alto\">alto</span></td><td>tall (m. sing.)</td><td><span data-say=\"alta\">alta</span></td><td>tall (f. sing.)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"altos\">altos</span></td><td>tall (m. pl.)</td><td><span data-say=\"altas\">altas</span></td><td>tall (f. pl.)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"pequeño\">pequeño</span></td><td>small (m.)</td><td><span data-say=\"pequeña\">pequeña</span></td><td>small (f.)</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Model sentences: <span data-say=\"Mi hermano es alto.\">Mi hermano es alto.</span> (My brother is tall.) — <span data-say=\"Mi hermana es alta.\">Mi hermana es alta.</span> (My sister is tall.) — <span data-say=\"Mis hermanos son altos.\">Mis hermanos son altos.</span> (My brothers are tall.)</p>", "question": "Why does ‘alto’ change to ‘alta’ in ‘Mi hermana es alta’?", "options": ["it must agree with the feminine noun ‘hermana’", "all adjectives ending in -o are irregular", "‘hermana’ is a plural noun, not singular", "the verb ‘ser’ forces every adjective to end in -a"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Adjectives agree with the gender of the noun they describe — hermana is feminine, so alto → alta."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement:learn:e3eb9411', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement', 'G.2 Adjectives and Agreement', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Adjectives ending in -e or a consonant", "reading": "<p>Some adjectives do <strong>not</strong> change for gender — only for number. This includes adjectives ending in <strong>-e</strong> (add -s for the plural) and most ending in a <strong>consonant</strong> (add -es for the plural).</p>\n            <table class=\"vocab-tbl\">\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"grande\">grande</span></td><td>big (m./f.)</td><td><span data-say=\"grandes\">grandes</span></td><td>big (pl.)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"inteligente\">inteligente</span></td><td>intelligent (m./f.)</td><td><span data-say=\"inteligentes\">inteligentes</span></td><td>intelligent (pl.)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"fácil\">fácil</span></td><td>easy (m./f.)</td><td><span data-say=\"fáciles\">fáciles</span></td><td>easy (pl., accent drops)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"azul\">azul</span></td><td>blue (m./f.)</td><td><span data-say=\"azules\">azules</span></td><td>blue (pl.)</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Example: <span data-say=\"Es una casa grande.\">Es una casa grande.</span> (It is a big house.) — <span data-say=\"Son unos libros fáciles.\">Son unos libros fáciles.</span> (They are some easy books.)</p>", "question": "Why does ‘grande’ stay the same in both ‘un chico grande’ AND ‘una chica grande’?", "options": ["adjectives ending in -e do not change for gender", "grande must always be placed directly before the noun", "grande only describes masculine nouns", "grande behaves like a verb, not an adjective"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Adjectives ending in -e (grande, inteligente) have one form for masculine and feminine — only the plural changes."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement:learn:dfaa22ca', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement', 'G.2 Adjectives and Agreement', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Adjectives of nationality", "reading": "<p>Nationality adjectives ending in a <strong>consonant</strong> add <strong>-a</strong> for the feminine (unlike other consonant adjectives). Nationality adjectives already ending in <strong>-o</strong> or <strong>-e</strong> just follow the normal rules.</p>\n            <table class=\"vocab-tbl\">\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"español\">español</span></td><td>Spanish (m.)</td><td><span data-say=\"española\">española</span></td><td>Spanish (f.)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"francés\">francés</span></td><td>French (m.)</td><td><span data-say=\"francesa\">francesa</span></td><td>French (f., accent drops)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"inglés\">inglés</span></td><td>English (m.)</td><td><span data-say=\"inglesa\">inglesa</span></td><td>English (f.)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"canadiense\">canadiense</span></td><td>Canadian (-e, invariable)</td><td><span data-say=\"belga\">belga</span></td><td>Belgian (invariable)</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Example: <span data-say=\"Tengo una amiga española.\">Tengo una amiga española.</span> (I have a Spanish friend.) Plural: <span data-say=\"franceses\">franceses</span> / <span data-say=\"francesas\">francesas</span>.</p>", "question": "How do you say ‘a French friend’ (female)?", "options": ["una amiga francesa", "un amigo francés", "una amiga francés", "unas amigas francesas"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "francés adds -a for the feminine: francesa. ‘amiga’ is feminine so the adjective must agree — francés with no -a is left masculine."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement:learn:d3952d5e', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement', 'G.2 Adjectives and Agreement', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Where does the adjective go?", "reading": "<p>Unlike English, most Spanish adjectives go <strong>AFTER</strong> the noun: <span data-say=\"una casa grande\">una casa grande</span> (a big house) — NOT “una grande casa”. <span data-say=\"un coche rojo\">un coche rojo</span> (a red car). <span data-say=\"unos libros interesantes\">unos libros interesantes</span> (some interesting books).</p>\n            <p>A few common adjectives can go <strong>before</strong> the noun and sometimes shorten: <span data-say=\"bueno\">bueno</span> → <span data-say=\"buen\">buen</span> (before a masculine singular noun): <span data-say=\"un buen amigo\">un buen amigo</span>. Likewise <span data-say=\"malo\">malo</span> → <span data-say=\"mal\">mal</span>: <span data-say=\"un mal día\">un mal día</span>. <span class=\"tier-h\">H</span> <span data-say=\"grande\">grande</span> shortens to <span data-say=\"gran\">gran</span> before either gender and changes meaning: <span data-say=\"un gran hombre\">un gran hombre</span> (a great man) vs <span data-say=\"un hombre grande\">un hombre grande</span> (a big man).</p>", "question": "Where does a normal Spanish adjective usually go?", "options": ["after the noun it describes", "before the noun, like in English", "at the very end of the sentence", "immediately after the verb ‘ser’"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Most Spanish adjectives follow the noun: una casa grande, not una grande casa."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement:learn:2866cba7', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement', 'G.2 Adjectives and Agreement', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Comparatives and superlatives", "reading": "<p>Comparatives: <span data-say=\"más que\">más + adjective + que</span> (more … than), <span data-say=\"menos que\">menos + adjective + que</span> (less … than), <span data-say=\"tan como\">tan + adjective + como</span> (as … as).</p>\n            <table class=\"vocab-tbl\">\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"Soy más alto que mi hermano.\">Soy más alto que mi hermano.</span></td><td>I am taller than my brother.</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"Es menos interesante que la otra película.\">Es menos interesante que la otra película.</span></td><td>It is less interesting than the other film.</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"Ella es tan inteligente como su hermana.\">Ella es tan inteligente como su hermana.</span></td><td>She is as intelligent as her sister.</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Superlative: el/la (los/las) + más + adjective — <span data-say=\"Es el chico más alto de la clase.\">Es el chico más alto de la clase.</span> (He is the tallest boy in the class.)</p>", "question": "How do you say ‘as easy as’ in Spanish?", "options": ["tan fácil como", "más fácil que", "menos fácil que", "el más fácil de"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "tan + adjective + como = as … as. más…que = more…than; menos…que = less…than."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement:learn:da720265', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement', 'G.2 Adjectives and Agreement', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Higher: irregular comparatives, possessives, demonstratives", "reading": "<p><span class=\"tier-h\">H</span> Four common adjectives have an <strong>irregular comparative</strong> — never say “más bueno” or “más malo”:</p>\n            <table class=\"vocab-tbl\">\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"bueno, mejor\">bueno → mejor</span></td><td>good → better</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"malo, peor\">malo → peor</span></td><td>bad → worse</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"viejo, mayor\">viejo → mayor</span></td><td>old → older</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"joven, menor\">joven → menor</span></td><td>young → younger</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p><strong>Possessive adjectives</strong> agree in number (nuestro/-a agrees in gender too): <span data-say=\"mi casa\">mi casa</span> / <span data-say=\"mis casas\">mis casas</span> (my), <span data-say=\"tu libro\">tu libro</span> / <span data-say=\"tus libros\">tus libros</span> (your), <span data-say=\"su coche\">su coche</span> / <span data-say=\"sus coches\">sus coches</span> (his/her/their), <span data-say=\"nuestra familia\">nuestra familia</span> / <span data-say=\"nuestro perro\">nuestro perro</span> (our).</p>\n            <p><strong>Demonstratives</strong>: <span data-say=\"este libro\">este libro</span> / <span data-say=\"esta casa\">esta casa</span> / <span data-say=\"estos zapatos\">estos zapatos</span> / <span data-say=\"estas chicas\">estas chicas</span> (this/these, close by); <span data-say=\"ese chico\">ese chico</span> / <span data-say=\"esa chica\">esa chica</span> (that, further away).</p>", "question": "Why is ‘más mejor’ always wrong?", "options": ["mejor is already a comparative — you never add más in front", "mejor must always be placed immediately before the noun it describes", "mejor only exists in the plural form", "más can only combine with -e ending adjectives"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "mejor, peor, mayor and menor are already comparative forms — combining them with más creates a double comparative, which is wrong."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement:misc:353ebe42', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement', 'G.2 Adjectives and Agreement', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> una casa alto</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> una casa alta</p>", "question": "Why is ‘una casa alto’ wrong?", "options": ["‘casa’ is feminine, so the adjective must be ‘alta’", "adjectives never change to agree with nouns", "‘alto’ must always be placed immediately before the noun ‘casa’", "‘casa’ is a masculine noun in Spanish"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "casa is feminine, so alto must become alta to agree."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement:misc:8e7a054a', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement', 'G.2 Adjectives and Agreement', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> los chicas altos</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> las chicas altas</p>", "question": "What is wrong with ‘los chicas altos’?", "options": ["the article AND the adjective must both be feminine plural", "‘chicas’ should be spelt ‘chicos’ instead", "‘altos’ needs a written accent on its final letter to agree", "nothing — this sentence is already correct"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "chicas is feminine plural, so both the article (las) and the adjective (altas) must agree with it."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement:misc:941de832', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement', 'G.2 Adjectives and Agreement', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> más mejor</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> mejor</p>", "question": "Why can’t you say ‘más mejor’ for ‘better’?", "options": ["mejor is already the comparative — adding más creates a double comparative", "mejor is actually classified as an adverb, not an adjective, so más cannot apply to it", "más can only be used with colours", "mejor must always follow the noun it describes"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "mejor already means ‘better’; putting más in front (‘more better’) is a double comparative and is always wrong."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement:misc:18042972', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement', 'G.2 Adjectives and Agreement', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> una grande casa</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> una casa grande</p>", "question": "Why is ‘una grande casa’ wrong for ‘a big house’?", "options": ["most descriptive adjectives go AFTER the noun in Spanish", "grande must always be shortened to gran", "‘casa’ always needs to be placed at the very start of the sentence", "grande should change to grandes here"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "In this everyday sense (size), grande follows the noun: una casa grande. Gran before the noun changes the meaning to ‘great’."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement:misc:e91c5b7b', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement', 'G.2 Adjectives and Agreement', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> mi amigas</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> mis amigas</p>", "question": "What is missing from ‘mi amigas’?", "options": ["the plural -s on the possessive: ‘mis’", "an accent on the final letter of ‘amigas’", "the article ‘las’ before ‘amigas’", "a comma after ‘mi’"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Possessive adjectives agree in number with the noun — ‘amigas’ is plural, so it must be mis amigas."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement:tips:3100684f', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement', 'G.2 Adjectives and Agreement', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — Paper 1 — Listening for agreement", "reading": "Listen closely to adjective endings: -o/-a tells you the gender of what is being described, -s/-es tells you if it is plural. ‘Tengo dos hermanas altas’ tells you there is more than one sister before you even hear ‘dos’.", "question": "You hear ‘…mis primas simpáticas…’. What does the -as ending on ‘simpáticas’ tell you?", "options": ["more than one female cousin is being described", "only one male cousin is being described", "the sentence is set in the past", "nothing — adjective endings carry no information"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The -as ending agrees with feminine plural ‘primas’ — more than one female cousin."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement:tips:0d7a41de', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement', 'G.2 Adjectives and Agreement', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — Paper 3 — Reading & translation into English", "reading": "Nationality adjectives are a common trap: ‘francés’ changes to ‘francesa’ for a woman and drops its accent. Also watch adjective position — ‘un gran hombre’ (a great man) is not the same as ‘un hombre grande’ (a big man).", "question": "‘Mi profesora es una gran mujer’ means…", "options": ["My teacher is a great woman", "My teacher is a very tall woman", "My teacher is an old woman", "My teacher is a large woman"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "gran before the noun means ‘great’ (character), not physical size — that would be grande after the noun."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement:tips:3839360d', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-2-adjectives-and-agreement', 'G.2 Adjectives and Agreement', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "evaluate — Paper 4 — Writing & translation into Spanish", "reading": "For the top band, combine a comparative or superlative with a possessive and a demonstrative: ‘Este es mi mejor amigo; es más simpático que los otros.’ Higher students should also try mayor/menor and gran for range.", "question": "Which answer shows the widest range of grammar for top marks?", "options": ["Este es mi mejor amigo; es más simpático que los otros", "Tengo un amigo muy simpático. Es alto y también es inteligente", "Mi amigo es bueno", "Tengo amigos simpáticos"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "It links a demonstrative, a possessive, an irregular comparative (mejor) and a full comparative structure — range plus accuracy, not just extra short sentences."}'::jsonb),
